# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: contact-hitter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:contact-hitter/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:contact-hitter/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] The brewery was founded in San Diego in 1995 by Skip Virgilio and Ted Newcomb.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Skip Virgilio was AleSmith's original brewmaster.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Peter Zien became brewmaster upon purchasing the company in July, 2002.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Zien is a BJCP "Grand Master level 1" beer judge, the only one in San Diego County.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] The original brewery is located at 9366 Cabot Drive in San Diego's Miramar area.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] In 2015 the company added a larger brewery and tasting room, also in Miramar, at 9990 AleSmith Court.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] At 25,000 square feet, the tasting room is billed as the largest beer tasting room in San Diego County.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Brewing operations at the new facility will eventually expand the company's brewing capacity ten-fold, according to Zien.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Beers from the brewery have been rated on RateBeer.com website as #1 Top Brewer in the World 2006 and again in 2013.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] In 2008, AleSmith was awarded "Small Brewing Company and Small Brewing Company Brewer of the Year" at the Great American Beer Festival.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] In 2015, AleSmith announced that Danish gypsy brewer Mikkeller had partnered with them to turn the original facility, located on Cabot Drive, into Mikkeller San Diego.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] The company has won ten medals in World Beer Cup competition, including six golds.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] At the 2008 Great American Beer Festival, AleSmith Brewing Company won the Small Brewing Company and Small Brewing Company Brewer of the Year Award.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] AleSmith's beers are inspired by the brewing styles of Great Britain and Belgium.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] Some AleSmith beers, such as their Cream Ale and Robust Porter Beer, are only offered on draft or in kegs at the brewery.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] The majority, however, are available in 22-ounce or 750 ml bottles.
[src:contact-hitter/alesmith-brewing-company] AleSmith's bottles are often accompanied by the trademark AleSmith anvil.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:contact-hitter/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] American pale ales are generally around 5% abv with significant quantities of American hops, typically Cascade.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] Although American brewed beers tend to use a cleaner yeast, and American two row malt, it is particularly the American hops that distinguish an APA from British or European pale ales.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] The style is close to the American India Pale Ale (IPA), and boundaries blur, though IPAs are stronger and more assertively hopped.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] The style is also close to amber ale, though ambers are darker and maltier due to use of crystal malts.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] Anchor Liberty Ale, a 6% abv ale originally brewed by Anchor Brewing Company as a special in 1975 to commemorate Paul Revere's midnight ride in 1775 which marked the start of the American War of Independence, was seen by Michael Jackson as the first modern American ale.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] The beer was popular, and became a regular in 1983.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] Jack McAuliffe of the New Albion Brewing Company was brewing his New Albion Ale by 1976, inspired by the ales he had tasted in Scotland.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] The beer was (at the time) vigorously hopped with American Cascade hops, refermented in the bottle, and not straw in color – all qualities the popular beer style of the time, i.e. pale lagers, did not possess.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] While the company brewed for fewer than 6 years at only 7.5 barrels (217 US gallons) per week, it inspired many more pioneers and imitators.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] The first brewery to successfully commercialize the use of significant quantities of American hops in the style of APA was the Sierra Nevada Brewing Company, which brewed the first experimental batch of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale in November 1980, distributing the finished version in March 1981.
[src:contact-hitter/american-pale-ale] Another pioneer of the hoppy American pale ale was Bert Grant of Yakima Brewing.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:contact-hitter/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:contact-hitter/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] In baseball, a **contact hitter** is a hitter who does not strike out often.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Thus, they are usually able to use their bat to make contact with the ball (hence the name *contact* hitter) to put it in play, and then run fast to reach base.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] As a result of their focus on putting the ball in play, they usually have fewer home runs than power hitters, but a higher BABIP.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Tony Gwynn is a leading example of a modern contact hitter.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] With just 135 career home runs, Gwynn described himself as a contact hitter who could hit to all fields.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] He rarely struck out (just 434 times, once every 21 at-bats, or once every 23.5 plate appearances) and his goal was to put the ball in play and move baserunners over.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Gwynn's success as a contact hitter landed him in the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Rod Carew is another example of a contact hitter who turned into a dominant MLB player, notching 18 all-star game appearances throughout his hall of fame career.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] One of the earliest known uses of the phrase "contact hitter" was in a 1966 *Bradenton Herald* report about Manatee Junior College players Whitey Whiten and Mark Sprunger.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] United Press International possibly was the first news agency to record the term in reference to a Major League Baseball player as Royals general manager Cedric Tallis gave recent acquisition Lou Piniella the title in a quote from a story that appeared in a 1969 edition of *The Tampa Tribune*.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Low-strikeout and high-batting average players have existed throughout the history of baseball, but players first began to achieve stardom as contact hitters in the 1970s.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Rod Carew was one of the first contact hitter superstars of this era, claiming the 1977 American League MVP with a .388 batting average for the Minnesota Twins.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] In his 19-year career, Carew never finished a season with a batting average lower than .273 and never posted a strikeout percentage higher than 16.2%.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Carew was selected as an All-Star for 18 consecutive seasons, cementing him as a superstar of the game.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Other great contact hitters of the 1970s include Joe Morgan and all-time hits leader Pete Rose.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Contact hitters continued to be a key facet of the game through the 1980s.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] This decade saw the rise of Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres, considered by many to be the greatest contact hitter of baseball's modern era.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Gwynn never posted a batting average lower than .289 in his career, never struck out more than 40 times in a season, and never posted a strikeout percentage higher than 8.0%.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Gwynn's .394 batting average in 1994 became legendary in the San Diego area and was commemorated by AleSmith Brewing Company's San Diego .394 American Pale Ale.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] The 1980s featured other popular contact hitters such as Paul Molitor and George Brett.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] In the 1990s, contact hitters began to experience a decline as featured superstars of the game due to the rise in popularity of power hitters and the increased usage of steroids in baseball to achieve record-breaking home run statistics.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] While sluggers like Barry Bonds, Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, and Ken Griffey Jr. dominated the 1990s and partook in highly-publicized races for home run titles, a few contact hitters like Wade Boggs continued to contribute to their teams with less media popularity than previous contact hitters.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] In pursuit of home runs, players became less concerned about striking out.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] The average team in 1975 struck out 4.98 times per game whereas the average rose to 6.30 by 1995.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Ichiro Suzuki of the Orix Blue Wave in Nippon Professional Baseball established himself as a legendary contact hitter in Japan in the 1990s.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] He did not come to Major League Baseball until 2001.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] When Suzuki signed with the Seattle Mariners in 2001, he made an instant impact as a superstar contact hitter.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] He won both the AL Rookie of the Year and the AL MVP in his MLB rookie season.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Suzuki was defiantly immune to striking out in an era where strikeouts were continually on the rise.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] He never struck out more than 86 times and never posted a strikeout percentage higher than 17.7%.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Accruing 3,000 MLB hits by 2016 and retiring as a player in 2019, Suzuki is considered the most recent contact-hitting superstar to play in Major League Baseball.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] In 2019, the average MLB team struck out 8.81 times per game, an all-time high in MLB history dating back to 1871.
[src:contact-hitter/contact-hitter] Despite the growing acceptance of strikeouts, the league still has many notable contact hitters, such as Michael Brantley, Yuli Gurriel, Jeff McNeil, David Fletcher, and Luis Arraez.
